1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian! Black controls the d4-square, and keeps their center pawns @@StartBracket@@e7 and d7@@EndBracket@@ safe from capture.   In the Open Sicilian, where White plays d2-d4 early @@StartBracket@@move 3 or 4@@EndBracket@@, Black will capture the pawn and have 2 center pawns @@StartBracket@@e and d@@EndBracket@@ to White's one center pawn @@StartBracket@@e4@@EndBracket@@.   Playing the Sicilian shows that Black wants to fight for an advantage rather than playing the symmetrical  1...e5  and trying for equality.  In this Quickstarter Guide, you will find a couple of variations per chapter which I think demonstrate thematic play in each line. Getting a good grip on them should set you up for success.   Enjoy! }
2. Nf3
{ White's main move by far, aiming for an Open Sicilian. It's called that because after d4, Black's c-pawn and White's d-pawn are exchanged, opening some lines for active play. }
2... Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2
{ A solid, albeit passive move which doesn't give White much chance for an advantage.   The Rauzer @@StartBracket@@6. Bg5@@EndBracket@@ and Fischer-Sozin @@StartBracket@@6. Bc4@@EndBracket@@ as seen in the first two chapters are more common at the GM level if White wants to fight for an advantage. }
6... Nxd4
{ This move is rare, but gives Black excellent play.   Black transposes to the Dragon Sicilian, but does not allow White to play the feared Yugoslav Attack @@StartBracket@@f2-f3, Bc1-e3, Qd1-d2, Bf1-c4, O-O-O@@EndBracket@@, since they have played the passive 6. Be2. }
7. Qxd4 g6
{ Not only is this a favorable Dragon, but White will need to move their d4-queen away soon due to the powerful bishop on g7. }
8. Bg5 Bg7 9. Nd5 { 9.O-O  Transposes to8.O-O. } 9... O-O 10. Nxf6+
{ This is bad for White and Black immediately seizes the initiative. } 10...
exf6 11. Bf4 f5
{ Attacking White's center and the central queen is attacked by discovery! }
12. Qb4
{ 12.Qxd6?!  Bxb2  This is already winning for Black according to the engine, since ...Bxa1 and ...Bc3+ are both serious threats. }
12... Re8
{ Black is already winning. The white king is in trouble and their center is collapsing. }
