1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian! Black controls the d4-square, and keeps their center pawns @@StartBracket@@e7 and d7@@EndBracket@@ safe from capture.   In the Open Sicilian, where White plays d2-d4 early @@StartBracket@@move 3 or 4@@EndBracket@@, Black will capture the pawn and have 2 center pawns @@StartBracket@@e and d@@EndBracket@@ to White's one center pawn @@StartBracket@@e4@@EndBracket@@.   Playing the Sicilian shows that Black wants to fight for an advantage rather than playing the symmetrical  1...e5  and trying for equality.  In this Quickstarter Guide, you will find a couple of variations per chapter which I think demonstrate thematic play in each line. Getting a good grip on them should set you up for success.   Enjoy! }
2. Nf3
{ White's main move by far, aiming for an Open Sicilian. It's called that because after d4, Black's c-pawn and White's d-pawn are exchanged, opening some lines for active play. }
2... Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6
{ Here we examine less common moves for White on move 6.   The first three chapters covered  6.Bg5  ,  6.Bc4  ,  and  6.Be2  . }
6. f3 { Never play f3!? } 6... e5
{ Black plays aggressively against White's passive 6. f3  . } 7. Nb3 Be7
{ Black wants to castle, play ...Be6, and play on the queenside, like in most Sicilians. }
8. Be3 O-O 9. Qd2
{ White indicates they will castle queenside, so Black starts play on that wing. }
9... a5 10. Bb5 { Develops a piece and stops a5-a4 for the moment. } 10... Be6
{ Black has all their pieces out and has castled and is ready for a tough middlegame with equal chances. }
11. O-O-O Nb4
{ Black attacks where the white king is trying to hide. Black also wants to play ...d6-d5 and the b4-knight protects the d5-square. }
12. a3 Qc7 13. axb4 Bxb3
{ A very sharp position where Black is doing well due to the unfortunate placement of the king on c1. }
14. cxb3 axb4
{ This is just good for Black. They win back their piece and have a free attack. }
