[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Grand Prix - 3.f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian! Black controls the d4-square, and keeps their center pawns @@StartBracket@@e7 and d7@@EndBracket@@ safe from capture.   In the Open Sicilian, where White plays d2-d4 early @@StartBracket@@move 3 or 4@@EndBracket@@, Black will capture the pawn and have 2 center pawns @@StartBracket@@e and d@@EndBracket@@ to White's one center pawn @@StartBracket@@e4@@EndBracket@@.   Playing the Sicilian shows that Black wants to fight for an advantage rather than playing the symmetrical  1...e5  and trying for equality.  In this Quickstarter Guide, you will find a couple of variations per chapter which I think demonstrate thematic play in each line. Getting a good grip on them should set you up for success.   Enjoy! }
2. Nc3 Nc6 3. f4
{ The Grand Prix Attack. Very popular with players under 2200, however, not played at the Super-GM level, except for the occasional blitz or bullet game! }
3... e6
{ This is less common than  3...g6  . It is safer, and it is Kasparov's choice in this variation.   Most of your opponents will be more booked up on 3...g6. }
4. Nf3 d5 { The point of 3...e6. } 5. Bb5
{ Some people only call it the Grand Prix Attack once white plays Bb5, in all variations.  5.e5?!  This may be played by lower rated players, but the engine says Black is already better!  Nh6!  The knight is headed for the f5-square where it's excellently placed.  6.d4  This looks like a French Defense. However, White would prefer to have his d4-pawn defended by the c-pawn, as in the Advance French variation.  6...cxd4  7.Nxd4  White wishes he could play cxd4 to keep his center intact.  7...Bd7  8.Be3  Nxd4  Time to play ...Nf5, but we must get rid of the White d4-knight first.  9.Bxd4  Nf5  The engine says Black is clearly better. Black has easy play with ...Qa5, ...Bb4, ...Rc8, ...O-O. }
5... Ne7
{ This ensures Black will not ruin his pawn structure by backing up his c6-knight with the other knight. }
6. exd5 exd5 7. Qe2
{ White pins the e7-knight and hopes to mess up Black's pawn structure on the queenside.   The problem is, the doubled pawns Black may get are fine, since they are all together in the center, and Black is simply better in many lines. }
7... Qd6 { Protecting the c6-knight some more, and attacking f4. } 8. Ne5
{ White insists on doubling Black's pawns! } 8... f6
{ This gives Black the advantage in all lines! Always play ...f6, uh... sometimes! }
9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Nf3 Kf7
{ Unpinning the e7-knight. The king is very safe on f7.   Black can later play ...Ng6 or ...Nf5, develop the bishops and they have a large advantage with their two bishops and big center. Once again, the white c1-bishop is suspicious. }
*

