[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Closed Sicilian - 3.g3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian! Black controls the d4-square, and keeps their center pawns @@StartBracket@@e7 and d7@@EndBracket@@ safe from capture.   In the Open Sicilian, where White plays d2-d4 early @@StartBracket@@move 3 or 4@@EndBracket@@, Black will capture the pawn and have 2 center pawns @@StartBracket@@e and d@@EndBracket@@ to White's one center pawn @@StartBracket@@e4@@EndBracket@@.   Playing the Sicilian shows that Black wants to fight for an advantage rather than playing the symmetrical  1...e5  and trying for equality.  In this Quickstarter Guide, you will find a couple of variations per chapter which I think demonstrate thematic play in each line. Getting a good grip on them should set you up for success.   Enjoy! }
2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ The Closed Sicilian. The only Super-GM to play this regularly is Boris Spassky, and that was 30-60 years ago!   It is played sometimes in the U2000 level though, so it's a must-know! }
3... e6
{ This is less common than  3...g6  ,  so, your opponent will face it less and have less experience. This move should give Black at least equality, no matter what White does. The Closed Sicilian is popular at the lower levels @@StartBracket@@U2000@@EndBracket@@, but players over 2200 almost never play it since Black has more than one way to get a good position. }
4. Bg2 Nf6
{ Black develops their kingside, castles, and plays for ...d5 or ...b5 @@StartBracket@@occasionally both@@EndBracket@@. Black doesn't have any pressure on them, so White can't get an advantage. }
5. d3 Be7 6. f4 d5
{ Black gets a nice center to thwart White's kingside advances. } 7. e5
{ 7.exd5?  This is a bad idea after White plays f2-f4. White needs to build a kingside pawn chain, and this just helps Black.  exd5  In reality, White had traded their e4-pawn for Black's e6-pawn. Black still has the pawn duo on d5 and c5.  8.Nf3  O-O  9.O-O  Re8  The engine already says Black has a clear advantage!   The main reason is the bad White bishop on c1. }
7... Nd7
{ Black has a great center, and will soon expand on the queenside with ...b7-b5-b4, etc. }
8. Nf3 O-O 9. O-O Rb8
{ Preparing ...b7-b5 and, at the same time, getting the rook off the dangerous h1-a8 diagonal. In the Closed Sicilian, Black often plays ...Rb8 for these reasons. }
10. a4 { Trying to slow down Black. } 10... a6
{ Once again, preparing ...b7-b5. } 11. Ne2 b5 12. axb5 axb5
{ Black is at least equal, as their queenside play is faster than White's attack on the kingside. Often, Black even plays ...f7-f6 and gets rid of the nice e5-pawn. }
*

