[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian! Black controls the d4-square, and keeps their center pawns @@StartBracket@@e7 and d7@@EndBracket@@ safe from capture.   In the Open Sicilian, where White plays d2-d4 early @@StartBracket@@move 3 or 4@@EndBracket@@, Black will capture the pawn and have 2 center pawns @@StartBracket@@e and d@@EndBracket@@ to White's one center pawn @@StartBracket@@e4@@EndBracket@@.   Playing the Sicilian shows that Black wants to fight for an advantage rather than playing the symmetrical  1...e5  and trying for equality.  In this Quickstarter Guide, you will find a couple of variations per chapter which I think demonstrate thematic play in each line. Getting a good grip on them should set you up for success.   Enjoy! }
2. b4
{ The Wing Gambit! Not played at the top level at all, but occasionally played in the U2000 crowd! }
2... cxb4 3. a3 d5 { This center break has been the refutation for decades. }
4. exd5 Qxd5 5. Nf3
{ 5.axb4??  Qe5+!  Was played in Shirazi-Peters, US Championship 1984. White resigned here, losing the shortest game in US Championship history! }
5... e5 { Black is basically up a pawn for nothing. } 6. c4
{ This is what strong players play to confuse the position. } 6... Qd8
{ This is a rare move @@StartBracket@@Usually Black plays  6...Qe6  ,  which is also good for Black@@EndBracket@@ but it's best.   The queen is nice and safe on d8! }
7. axb4 { 7.Nxe5??  would get forked by  7...Qd4  . } 7... Bxb4
{ A novelty. This position is already much better for Black. } 8. Nxe5 Qe7 9.
Qe2 { 9.f4??  loses the knight to the pin after  f6! } 9... Nf6
{ Black has easy development for all their pieces, whereas White can't develop their f1-bishop or castle.   Black is clearly better here. }
