[Black "Smith-Morra Gambit - 2.d4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian! Black controls the d4-square, and keeps their center pawns @@StartBracket@@e7 and d7@@EndBracket@@ safe from capture.   In the Open Sicilian, where White plays d2-d4 early @@StartBracket@@move 3 or 4@@EndBracket@@, Black will capture the pawn and have 2 center pawns @@StartBracket@@e and d@@EndBracket@@ to White's one center pawn @@StartBracket@@e4@@EndBracket@@.   Playing the Sicilian shows that Black wants to fight for an advantage rather than playing the symmetrical  1...e5  and trying for equality.  In this Quickstarter Guide, you will find a couple of variations per chapter which I think demonstrate thematic play in each line. Getting a good grip on them should set you up for success.   Enjoy! }
2. d4
{ The Smith-Morra Gambit! This is quite popular at the U2200 level, but, GMs never play it, unless it's blitz or bullet.   Most GMs don't want to sacrifice a pawn on move 2! }
2... cxd4 3. c3
{ This is the real starting position of the Gambit. Of course, White could play  3.Nf3  transposing into the Open Sicilian or  3.Qxd4  ,  which isn't good since  3...Nc6  kicks the queen.   But gambit players love playing the Smith-Morra! }
3... dxc3
{ Taking the pawn is the only way for Black to get an advantage! More tame moves that are also good are  3...Nf6  ,  3...e5  ,  and  3...d3  . }
4. Nxc3 e6
{ Black usually plays  4...Nc6  ,  but this has been played successfully by Caruana, Timman, and Short. }
5. Nf3 a6
{ This really makes the f1-bishop of little use in getting compensation. White likes to play Bc4 in this Gambit, but here, it is ineffective. }
6. Bc4
{ It doesn't look like the bishop does much here, but it is still, by far, the most common move. White wants to castle, and doesn't see another good square for their bishop. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 Bb7 8. O-O Be7
{ The engine move, and the one played by Caruana @@StartBracket@@I suspect Fabi knew this was the engine move!@@EndBracket@@.   Black develops his pieces and will soon just be ahead a pawn for little compensation. Black wants to block the e-file in case White sacrifices a piece with a later Nc3-d5. }
9. e5 { This ends White's dreams of playing Nc3-d5 later. } 9... Nc6 10. Qe2
Na5 { Black wants the two bishops, what else? } 11. Bc2 f5
{ White has almost no compensation for a pawn.   Black has a great b7-bishop and White doesn't have anything threatening against the black king. }
12. exf6 { White opens up the center trying to get active play for his pawn. }
12... Nxf6
{ Black has every minor piece out and has two central pawns to zero. Black is clearly better here and should be very happy with their position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Rauzer Variation"]
[Black "Rauzer - The Unusual 7.Bb5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian! Black controls the d4-square, and keeps their center pawns @@StartBracket@@e7 and d7@@EndBracket@@ safe from capture.   In the Open Sicilian, where White plays d2-d4 early @@StartBracket@@move 3 or 4@@EndBracket@@, Black will capture the pawn and have 2 center pawns @@StartBracket@@e and d@@EndBracket@@ to White's one center pawn @@StartBracket@@e4@@EndBracket@@.   Playing the Sicilian shows that Black wants to fight for an advantage rather than playing the symmetrical  1...e5  and trying for equality. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The Open Sicilian. } 3... cxd4
{ The point of 1...c5, depriving White of a full pawn-center. } 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ Attacking the e4-pawn. } 5. Nc3
{ 5.Nxc6  bxc6  6.e5?  Qa5+  And with this fork, Black wins a pawn. } 5... d6
{ This is the starting position in our course for the Open Sicilian. Of course, White can deviate earlier, and we will check those lines in other chapters.   This position has been dubbed the Classical Sicilian. Black can also play a different move order and get the same position via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  for example after  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6  but then when White doesn't play the Open Sicilian with  3.d4  and 4. Nxd4, there are different variations to learn.   In the chapters without normal Open Sicilians with  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  I will discuss these differences in move-order. }
6. Bg5 { The Rauzer Sicilian. } 6... e6
{ Black's pawns on e6 and d6 control the center and allow Black to develop their bishops. }
7. Bb5 { An unusual, albeit tricky line. } 7... Qb6
{ Often, moving the queen out early isn't a good idea. But this move accomplishes so much, that it is a great idea!   One of the things Black often does in Open Sicilians is to move the queen to one of the squares on the open diagonal @@StartBracket@@c7, b6, or a5@@EndBracket@@. Here we defend the c6-knight, put pressure on the d4-knight, and put pressure on the undefended b2-pawn as well! }
8. Bxf6
{ 8.Be3  Qc7  9.O-O  Be7  The white b5-bishop isn't well placed.   White will either need to trade their bishop, which they don't want to do, or lose tempi with Bb5-e2 later. Black is ready to gain a tempo with ...a7-a6. }
8... gxf6 9. Nd5
{ An interesting piece sacrifice.   The engines like Black, but, it's good to know how to meet this aggression! If White plays any other way, Black just plays ...Bd7 and ...Be7 and has two bishops and a great central pawn mass. }
9... exd5 10. exd5 a6 11. Bxc6+
{ 11.Ba4?  Qa5+  12.c3  Qxd5  Not only captures a pawn, but stops White from taking on c5 with the d5-pawn and defends c6!  13.Nxc6  Qe4+!   13...bxc6??  would blunder the queen to  14.Qxd5  due to the pin on the pawn.  14.Qe2  Qxe2+  15.Kxe2  Bd7!  and Black will simply be ahead a piece. }
11... bxc6 12. Qe2+ Kd7
{ The king runs to safety, and Black gets to keep an extra piece. } 13. dxc6+
Kc7
{ White has compensation, but not enough for a whole piece. Black also has the two bishops!   Black will likely continue with... d5 and ...Bc5. }
*

