[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Rauzer Variation"]
[Black "Rauzer - 7.Qd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian! Black controls the d4-square, and keeps their center pawns @@StartBracket@@e7 and d7@@EndBracket@@ safe from capture.   In the Open Sicilian, where White plays d2-d4 early @@StartBracket@@move 3 or 4@@EndBracket@@, Black will capture the pawn and have 2 center pawns @@StartBracket@@e and d@@EndBracket@@ to White's one center pawn @@StartBracket@@e4@@EndBracket@@.   Playing the Sicilian shows that Black wants to fight for an advantage rather than playing the symmetrical  1...e5  and trying for equality. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The Open Sicilian. } 3... cxd4
{ The point of 1...c5, depriving White of a full pawn-center. } 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ Attacking the e4-pawn. } 5. Nc3
{ 5.Nxc6  bxc6  6.e5?  Qa5+  And with this fork, Black wins a pawn. } 5... d6
{ This is the starting position in our course for the Open Sicilian. Of course, White can deviate earlier, and we will check those lines in other chapters.   This position has been dubbed the Classical Sicilian. Black can also play a different move order and get the same position via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  for example after  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6  but then when White doesn't play the Open Sicilian with  3.d4  and 4. Nxd4, there are different variations to learn.   In the chapters without normal Open Sicilians with  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  I will discuss these differences in move-order. }
6. Bg5 { The Rauzer Sicilian. } 6... e6
{ Black's pawns on e6 and d6 control the center and allow Black to develop their bishops. }
7. Qd3 a6
{ Black likes to play ...a7-a6 in a lot of Sicilian lines to defend the b5-square and prepare to play ...b7-b5 later. }
8. Nxc6
{ Usually White doesn't want to play Nxc6 in the Sicilian since it brings the black b7-pawn to c6 and bolsters the center for Black to play ...d6-d5 later.   8.O-O-O  Nxd4  9.Qxd4  Be7  would transpose to themainline with 7. Qd2  . }
8... bxc6 9. O-O-O
{ White can already castle queenside, which is typical when White has moved their queenside pieces before their bishop on f1.   This ensures a sharp position since likely, Black will castle kingside and both sides can start a flank attack against the opponent's king. }
9... d5 { Black likes to play ...d5 in the Sicilian when possible! } 10. Qe3
{ This pins the d5-pawn with the rook on d1. White also defends their bishop on g5. Finally, the bishop on f1 is ready to develop and isn't blocked anymore.   10.e5  can be met by  10...h6  with a counterattack on the bishop and after  11.Bh4  g5  breaks the pin and it's not clear what White has gained by pushing the pawn all the way to e5. However, even stronger is  11...Qc7  when after  12.exf6  Qf4+  wins back the piece with a fork.  13.Kb1  Qxh4  Black has a great position with the bishop pair and huge center. }
10... Be7 { This developing move also unpins the knight on f6. } 11. Bxf6
{ This tactical move makes sense since Black must take with the pawn and somewhat ruins their kingside. Luckily for Black, they get a lot of pawns in the center! }
11... gxf6
{ Bad is  11...Bxf6?  12.exd5  White has too many attackers on d5 and the e6-pawn is pinned.  cxd5  13.Nxd5!  and White has won a pawn. }
12. Bc4
{ Taking advantage of the rook pinning the d5-pawn to the queen. The bishop defends the white king on b3 and puts pressure on Black's center. }
12... Bb7
{ Adding necessary defense to the d5-square, indirectly through the c6-pawn.  It's a rich position where Black has two bishops and a lot of center pawns, and White has the safer king @@StartBracket@@for now!@@EndBracket@@.   The engines slightly prefer White, but any Sicilian player should be fine taking Black here.   Black can leave their king in the center for a while since they have so many pawns in front of their king, and, at the right moment, they can castle kingside and play ...Kh8 and the king should be safe enough. }
