[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Rauzer Variation"]
[Black "Rauzer - 7.Qd2 Mainline #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian! Black controls the d4-square, and keeps their center pawns @@StartBracket@@e7 and d7@@EndBracket@@ safe from capture.   In the Open Sicilian, where White plays d2-d4 early @@StartBracket@@move 3 or 4@@EndBracket@@, Black will capture the pawn and have 2 center pawns @@StartBracket@@e and d@@EndBracket@@ to White's one center pawn @@StartBracket@@e4@@EndBracket@@.   Playing the Sicilian shows that Black wants to fight for an advantage rather than playing the symmetrical  1...e5  and trying for equality. }
2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The Open Sicilian. } 3... cxd4
{ The point of 1...c5, depriving White of a full pawn-center. } 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ Attacking the e4-pawn. } 5. Nc3
{ 5.Nxc6  bxc6  6.e5?  Qa5+  And with this fork, Black wins a pawn. } 5... d6
{ This is the starting position in our course for the Open Sicilian. Of course, White can deviate earlier, and we will check those lines in other chapters.   This position has been dubbed the Classical Sicilian. Black can also play a different move order and get the same position via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  for example after  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6  but then when White doesn't play the Open Sicilian with  3.d4  and 4. Nxd4, there are different variations to learn.   In the chapters without normal Open Sicilians with  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  I will discuss these differences in move-order. }
6. Bg5 { The Rauzer Sicilian. } 6... e6
{ Black's pawns on e6 and d6 control the center and allow Black to develop their bishops. }
7. Qd2 { The mainline, preparing to castle long. } 7... a6
{ The move ...a7-a6 is a good all-purpose move in a lot of variations of the Sicilian. White no longer has access to b5 for his Bishop or Knight and Black can later play ...b7-b5, especially when White castles queenside. }
8. O-O-O
{ White always castles queenside in the Rauzer and Black gets the kind of dynamic/exciting game they're looking for. }
8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Be7
{ Black is ready to play the standard moves ...b7-b5, ...Bb7, ...O-O in different move orders, depending on what White plays first. }
10. f4 b5 { White is going for our king, so we need to go for theirs! } 11. Be2
Bb7 { A nice diagonal for the bishop. } 12. Bf3 O-O 13. e5
{ An aggressive, forcing line, which only leads to equality with accurate play. }
13... Bxf3 14. exf6
{ 14.gxf3  dxe5  15.fxe5   15.Qxd8  Rfxd8  16.fxe5  Nd5  17.Bxe7  Nxe7  White has several weak pawns, whereas Black's pawn structure is intact. Black has a nice edge here and can play for the win by attacking the weak white pawns.  15...Nd5  A lot of pieces can be captured but White must stop ...Bxg5+.  16.Bxe7  Nxe7   16...Qxe7?  17.Nxd5  exd5  18.Qxd5  wins a pawn for White.  17.Qc5  Attacking the queen on d8 but two can play at that game!  Rc8!  Black's position is to be preferred since White has no serious attack against the Black king and Black simply has a more compact pawn structure. }
14... gxf6
{ There are going to be a lot of trades, but the middlegame is still rich with the opposite side castled kings. }
15. gxf3 fxg5
{ Black is up a pawn with a better pawn structure, but White has enough play on the g-file to claim equality, but no more. }
16. Ne4
{ Activating the knight to the great e4-square and putting the test to Black's defenses. }
16... d5
{ It's important to kick out the knight from this great square as soon as possible, and this transforms the weak pawn on d6 to a nice center with ...d5. }
17. Nxg5
{ 17.h4!?  Qc7!   17...dxe4?  18.Qxe4!  Wins for White due to the dual threats of 19. Rxd8 and 19. hxg5.  18.Nxg5  Qc4!  Black likes endings with their king on g8 a little exposed and White's awful kingside pawn structure. White does not oblige!  19.Qe5  Rfc8  The engine says equal, but both sides are in for a fight in this position! }
17... Bf6 { Black keeps kicking the centralized white pieces to the curb. } 18.
Qd3 { Threatening 19. Qxh7#. } 18... Bxg5 { Forced in order to stop mate. } 19.
Rhg1
{ Pinning the bishop to the king and keeping the attacking potential alive. }
19... Qf6
{ The position is equal. Black has a better pawn structure and White has a marginally safer king.   Black's king should be safe enough on h8 and Black can put their rooks on the open c and g-files. }
