2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 { The Open Sicilian. } 3... cxd4
{ The point of 1...c5, depriving White of a full pawn-center. } 4. Nxd4 Nf6
{ Attacking the e4-pawn. } 5. Nc3
{ 5.Nxc6  bxc6  6.e5?  Qa5+  And with this fork, Black wins a pawn. } 5... d6
{ This is the starting position in our course for the Open Sicilian. Of course, White can deviate earlier, and we will check those lines in other chapters.   This position has been dubbed the Classical Sicilian. Black can also play a different move order and get the same position via @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@  2...d6  for example after  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  Nf6  5.Nc3  Nc6  but then when White doesn't play the Open Sicilian with  3.d4  and 4. Nxd4, there are different variations to learn.   In the chapters without normal Open Sicilians with  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pp1ppppp/2n5/2p5/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 2 3@@EndFEN@@  3.d4  cxd4  4.Nxd4  I will discuss these differences in move-order. }
6. Bg5 { The Rauzer Sicilian. } 6... e6
{ Black's pawns on e6 and d6 control the center and allow Black to develop their bishops. }
7. Qd2 { The mainline, preparing to castle long. } 7... a6
{ The move ...a7-a6 is a good all-purpose move in a lot of variations of the Sicilian. White no longer has access to b5 for his Bishop or Knight and Black can later play ...b7-b5, especially when White castles queenside. }
8. O-O-O
{ White always castles queenside in the Rauzer and Black gets the kind of dynamic/exciting game they're looking for. }
8... Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Be7
{ Black is ready to play the standard moves ...b7-b5, ...Bb7, ...O-O in different move orders, depending on what White plays first. }
10. f4 b5 { White is going for our king, so we need to go for theirs! } 11.
Bxf6 gxf6 12. e5 { White plays forcefully. } 12... d5
{ Once Black has played ...d6-d5, we have a nice center and won't need to worry about losing the d6-pawn anymore. }
13. Kb1
{ Always play Kb1.   This defends the queenside better, especially the a2-pawn, and gets off the dark square, c1, which is on the half-open c-file and in range of Black's dark-squared bishop. }
13... Bb7 14. f5
{ Black has two bishops and a lot of center pawns and White tries to break through as quickly as possible. }
14... fxe5
