{ White's main move by far, aiming for an Open Sicilian. It's called that because after d4, Black's c-pawn and White's d-pawn are exchanged, opening some lines for active play. }
2... Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Bc4
{ The Fischer-Sozin Variation. A solid developing move to the nice c4-square. }
6... Qb6
{ Black immediately attacks the central knight and tries to drive the knight away from the nice square. At the same time, if White plays the natural, and most common move,  7.Nb3  ,  then their c4-bishop won't have that square later. }
7. Ndb5 { A tricky line. } 7... a6 8. Be3 { Attacking the b6-queen. } 8... Qa5
9. Nd4 e6
{ A typical pawn structure in the Open Sicilian. But White has lost some time with Ng1-f3-d4-b5-d4.   9...Nxd4  would only help White develop with  10.Qxd4  . }
10. O-O
{ With the Black queen on a5 so soon, White decides queenside castling is unsafe. }
10... Be7 { Black, as per usual, wants to develop their pieces and castle. }
11. Bb3 { This makes the bishop safe as it was undefended on c4. } 11... O-O
{ This looks like a main line Sozin where Black didn't play ...Qb6, and White has lost tempi with their d4-knight. }
12. f4
{ White gains space and tries to start an attack in the center and kingside. }
12... Bd7
{ Black has completed development and castled and the engines say the position is equal.   Black will likely take the c-file with their queen's rook and later play ...b7-b5 with good play on the queenside and a solid center. }
