[White "3) 6.Be2 (Dragon Variation)"]
[Black "6.Be2 (Dragon) - 8.Be3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White's main move by far, aiming for an Open Sicilian. It's called that because after d4, Black's c-pawn and White's d-pawn are exchanged, opening some lines for active play. }
2... Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6 6. Be2
{ A solid, albeit passive move which doesn't give white much chance for an advantage.   The Rauzer @@StartBracket@@6. Bg5@@EndBracket@@ and Fischer-Sozin @@StartBracket@@6. Bc4@@EndBracket@@ as seen in the first two chapters are more common at the GM level if white wants to fight for an advantage. }
6... Nxd4
{ This move is rare, but gives Black excellent play.   Black transposes to the Dragon Sicilian, but does not allow White to play the feared Yugoslav Attack @@StartBracket@@f2-f3, Bc1-e3, Qd1-d2, Bf1-c4, O-O-O@@EndBracket@@, since he has played the passive 6. Be2. }
7. Qxd4 g6
{ Not only is this a favorable Dragon, but White will need to move his d4-queen away soon due to the powerful bishop on g7. }
8. Be3
{ 8.O-O  can easily lead to a virtually identical situation:  8...Bg7  9.Bg5  O-O  Black's moves are so easy to play.  In most variations, we play ...Bg7, ...O-O, ...Be6 with complete safety and complete development.  10.Qd2  Be6  Once again, I prefer Black. We have the c-file for our rook, and can play either the standard ...a7-a6, ...b7-b5 plan, or be even more aggressive with ...Qd8-b6 pressuring b2. }
8... Bg7 { Black always plays ...Bg7 after ...g7-g6. } 9. Qd2 O-O
{ Black's play is easy. Castle and develop pieces! } 10. O-O
{ 10.O-O-O ?!  Be6  This is a poor version of the Yugoslav Attack for White for several reasons:   A. The bishop on e2 is passive compared to the normal c4-square @@StartBracket@@which White decided not to play on move 6, so this is why we play the Dragon@@EndBracket@@.  B. The black e6-bishop usually doesn't find such a nice active square in the regular Yugoslav Attack.  C. White has not played f2-f3, so g2-g4 is difficult to play.   Now Black can play ...Qd8-a5, ...Rf8-c8 with a good attack against the white king. }
10... Be6
{ I like Black in this position since they have the half-open c-file @@StartBracket@@a benefit of almost any Open Sicilian@@EndBracket@@ and complete development and king safety.   Black will play on the queenside, most likely, which is standard in the Open Sicilian. }
*

