[Black "Rare 6th Moves - Club Player's 6.Be3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6
{ Here we examine less common moves for White on move 6.   The first three chapters covered  6.Bg5  ,  6.Bc4  ,  and  6.Be2  . }
6. Be3 { Rare at the top level, but quite common at the club level. } 6... Ng4
{ Playing ...Ng4 when it's a good move is key in a lot of Sicilian variations. }
7. Bg5 Qb6 { Attacking the d4-knight and also pressuring the f2 and b2-pawns. }
8. Bb5
{ 8.Nxc6??  Qxf2#  I have had this position in blitz and bullet many times! }
8... Bd7 { Not  8...Qxd4??  9.Qxd4  The c6-knight is pinned! } 9. O-O Qxd4
{ Black trades into an excellent endgame. } 10. Bxc6
{ 10.Qxd4??  Nxd4  White is just down a piece. } 10... Qxd1 11. Bxd7+
{ Check! } 11... Kxd7 12. Raxd1 h6
{ The bishop doesn't have a lot of good squares in which to retreat.  If they play  13.Bh4  or  13.Bf4  ,  then Black plays  13...g5  and 14...Bg7. So White usually plays.... }
13. Bc1 g5
{ The engine says it is about equal, but I prefer Black with their g7-bishop coming and half-open c-file for the queen's rook. The king on d7 is of no consequence, since it's an endgame, this may actually favor Black to have an active king! }
*

