{ 7.Nxc6?!  bxc6  When White takes the pawn on c6 early, this favors Black in most Sicilian variations  Black has the half-open b-file and the c6-pawn controls d5.  8.Bd2  Not the move White wants to play in an Open Sicilian. The white bishop is passive on d2.  g6  White's setup is not impressive against dragon-esque ways of playing for Black. This is typical in a lot of non-standard lines in the Sicilian.  9.h3  Kicking the knight away.  9...Nf6   9...Ne5?!  10.Na4!  This unusual move has the simple idea to play Bc3 and eventually trade Black's great bishop on  g7  .  10...Bg7  11.Bc3!  O-O  12.f4  White gains space, kicks out the black knight from the center and forces the trade of bishops.  12...Nd7  13.Bxg7  Kxg7  14.Qd2  White is slightly better with their nice center and Black is left without their great fianchettoed bishop.  10.Bd3  Bg7  This is an excellent Dragon for Black. White has no attack and Black has excellent chances to play in the center later with d6-d5.  White's bishops on d2 and d3 are a sad sight in the Dragon Sicilian. }
7... Nxe3 8. Nxc6 { This leads to an excellent endgame for Black. } 8... Nxd1
{ All the following captures are forced. } 9. Nxd8+ { Check! } 9... Kxd8 10.
Rxd1 a6
{ Kicking the bishop away and playing ...a6 with tempo is a dream in the Sicilian! }
11. Be2 e6
{ Black has the two bishops and the center pawns.   Black's king is perfectly safe on e7 or c7 and the engine already gives -0.5! }
