[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 5. Nc3 d6
{ Here we examine less common moves for White on move 6.   The first three chapters covered  6.Bg5  ,  6.Bc4  ,  and  6.Be2  . }
6. f3 { Never play f3!? } 6... e5
{ Black plays aggressively against White's passive 6.f3 } 7. Nb3 Be7
{ Black wants to castle, play Be6, and play on the queenside, like in most Sicilians. }
8. Be3 O-O 9. Qd2
{ White indicates he will castle queenside, so Black starts play on that wing. }
9... a5 10. Bb5 { Develops a piece and stops a5-a4 for the moment. } 10... Be6
11. O-O-O
{ Here we have a thematic opposite-side castling position. Black has a weak d-pawn, but good activity on the queenside. Additionally, if we can achieve the d5-break, all our problems are solved!  Let's take a look at several continuations from here. }
11... Nb4
{ Black attacks where the White king is trying to hide. Black also wants to play ...d6-d5 and the b4-knight protects the d5-square. }
12. Kb1 d5 { Now there are a LOT of trades on d5 leading to an equal game. }
13. exd5 Nbxd5 14. Nxd5 Nxd5 15. Bc4 { White attacks the d5-knight. } 15...
Nxe3 16. Qxe3 { White has a discovered attack on the queen. } 16... Qc8 17.
Bxe6 Qxe6
{ Lots of trades have led to an interesting position, where I would prefer Black since they seem to have the safer king. Additionally, the bishop will most likely be more useful than the knight in most endgames. }
*

