[White "5) Alapin Variation & Rare 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Rare 3rd Moves - Passive 3.d3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White's main move by far, aiming for an Open Sicilian. It's called that because after d4, Black's c-pawn and White's d-pawn are exchanged, opening some lines for active play. }
2... Nc6 3. d3
{ Not the most aggressive move! Black has many good ways to play here, but I recommend the fianchetto line with ...g7-g6. }
3... g6 4. g3
{ White almost always fianchettos his f1-bishop when he plays d2-d3 early. The bishop going to e2 is pretty passive. }
4... Bg7 5. Bg2 d6 6. O-O e5
{ Again, black has many good moves, but I like taking space in the center. } 7.
Nc3 { Simple development. } 7... Nge7
{ Black almost always puts the knight here after playing ...e7-e5. Black may want to play ...f7-f5 later, and doesn't want to block their g7-bishop. }
8. Nd2
{ The one weakness in Black's position is the d5-square. White has two ideas at his disposal with this move: Play Nc4-e3-d5 and/or play f2-f4. }
8... O-O 9. Nc4 Be6
{ Black has castled and completed development.   Soon Black will play ...Qd7, connecting their rooks, and play for either ...b7-b5 or ...f7-f5.   The engine prefers Black slightly. }
