[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White's main move by far, aiming for an Open Sicilian. It's called that because after d4, Black's c-pawn and White's d-pawn are exchanged, opening some lines for active play. }
2... Nc6 3. c3
{ We are going to use this line against @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c3  as well.   If White plays @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.Nf3  and then 3. c3, this limits Black's options.   So, if you face @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1ppppp/8/2p5/4P3/8/PPPP1PPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq c6 0 2@@EndFEN@@  2.c3  or 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. c3, you can play the same way and not memorize a lot of extra stuff. In this move-order, after  2...d5  White can't play Nb1-c3, so it's okay if Black's queen goes to d5.  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  Nc6  White has nothing better than to defend their center with  4.Nf3  transposing to the mainline with  4...Bf5  . }
3... d5
{ Black doesn't mind having his Queen on d5 if White can't play Nb1-c3.   In fact, Scandi players:   @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  d5  don't even mind then! }
4. exd5 Qxd5 5. d4
{ The point of White playing c2-c3 in most openings is to play d2-d4 early.  This position can also occur after @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  d5  3.exd5  Qxd5  4.d4  Nc6  5.Nf3  . }
5... Bf5
{ This relatively new line gives Black a nice game. Often, Black castles queenside and pressures the d4-pawn. }
6. Be3 { This puts pressure on the c5-pawn. } 6... cxd4 7. cxd4 Bxb1
{ Stopping Nb1-c3 once and for all! Another reason to play ...Bc8-f5 for Black. }
8. Rxb1 e6
{ 8...Qxa2?!  9.Be2  This is too risky for my taste. Black loses time to take the a2-pawn, and does not have any kingside development. The engine slightly prefers White, so, if you are a real pawn snatcher, you can give it a try, but I wouldn't do it.   I like development! }
9. a3 { This prevents ...Bf8-b4+ and/or ...Qd5xa2. } 9... Nf6
{ Black has easy development. } 10. Bd3 Bd6
{ Both sides have all their minor pieces out and will now castle. } 11. O-O O-O
{ Black has completely equalized, and with White's isolated d-pawn, I prefer Black. Black will likely play ...Rfd8 and ...Rac8 soon and have no issues. White must defend his d4-pawn, with no real chances ever to play d4-d5. }
