[White "5) Alapin Variation & Rare 3rd Moves"]
[Black "Rare 3rd Moves - 3.Bc4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White's main move by far, aiming for an Open Sicilian. It's called that because after d4, Black's c-pawn and White's d-pawn are exchanged, opening some lines for active play. }
2... Nc6 3. Bc4
{ This looks timid, but Magnus played it in the 2023 European Team Championship. }
3... e6 4. Nc3 a6
{ A very useful move in a lot of Sicilian variations. Black wants to play ...b7-b5 and also prevent White from ever playing Bc4-b5 or Nc3-b5. }
5. d4
{ This makes the position look like an Open Sicilian, although the White c4-bishop isn't well placed since Black has played ...e6 and ...a6, so ...b7-b5 will come with tempo and the Bishop doesn't do anything on the a2-g8 diagonal. }
5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Qc7
{ This queen is well-placed on c7 since White can never play Nb5 or Nd5 to attack the queen, and the c4-bishop is a bit loose. }
7. Bb3 Nf6 { Black develops their knight to the usual f6-square. } 8. O-O b5
{ Black gains space on the queenside and prepares ...Bc8-b7. Also of note, Black is threatening ...b5-b4 and the White c3-knight must move away from the defense of the e4-pawn. }
9. a3 { 9.f4??  Nxd4!  10.Qxd4  Bc5!  Oops! } 9... Bb7
{ The engine already says Black is clearly better.   Black has nice piece activity and the b3-bishop doesn't look so good for White. In practice Black scores over 65% in this position. Black will develop their bishop to e7 or d6 and castle with no issues and an excellent Sicilian position. }
