[White "6) Rossolimo Attack"]
[Black "Rossolimo Attack - Hasty 4.e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White's main move by far, aiming for an Open Sicilian. It's called that because after d4, Black's c-pawn and White's d-pawn are exchanged, opening some lines for active play. }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This has become quite popular over the last 20 years, and I face it almost as often as the Open Sicilian with  3.d4  . }
3... Nf6
{ This is the fourth most common move, and I want my Chessable peeps to get their opponents out of their prep ASAP, and also play something that is good for Black!   Typically, Black plays either  3...e6  @@StartBracket@@that's what I usually play@@EndBracket@@ or  3...g6  . But since your opponents will be booked to the teeth in those lines, let's make it tough for White right away! }
4. e5
{ Immediately trying to punish 3...Nf6. But this give Black the nice d5-square. }
4... Nd5 { A nice central post. } 5. Nc3 Nc7
{ Encouraging White to give us the bishop pair, and from here it can often later hop to the nice e6-square. }
6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. h3 Bf5 8. d3 c4
{ A pawn sacrifice that has never been played, until one of you Chessable people plays it! }
9. dxc4 Qxd1+ { Revoking White's castling rights! } 10. Kxd1 O-O-O+
{ there are few things better than castling with check. } 11. Bd2 Ne6
{ The engine prefers White due to the space advantage, but I like the bishop pair. Next we can solidify the f5-bishop's post with ...h5, and maybe even push on the kingside with ...g5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) Rossolimo Attack"]
[Black "Rossolimo Attack - Hasty 4.e5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White's main move by far, aiming for an Open Sicilian. It's called that because after d4, Black's c-pawn and White's d-pawn are exchanged, opening some lines for active play. }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This has become quite popular over the last 20 years, and I face it almost as often as the Open Sicilian with  3.d4  . }
3... Nf6
{ This is the fourth most common move, and I want my Chessable peeps to get their opponents out of their prep ASAP, and also play something that is good for Black!   Typically, Black plays either  3...e6  @@StartBracket@@that's what I usually play@@EndBracket@@ or  3...g6  . But since your opponents will be booked to the teeth in those lines, let's make it tough for White right away! }
4. e5
{ Immediately trying to punish 3...Nf6. But this give Black the nice d5-square. }
4... Nd5 { A nice central post. } 5. O-O Nc7
{ The idea of ...Nf6-d5-c7 is seen throughout this chapter.   The b5-bishop almost always takes on c6 now, since, that was White's plan after 3. Bb5 in any case. }
6. Bxc6 dxc6
{ Black always takes with the d7-pawn so their c8-bishop has some good squares to develop. The c7-knight now has e6 and d5-squares to go to later. }
7. Nc3 Bg4
{ Pinning the f3-knight and getting the bishop out, as we see often. } 8. h3
Bh5 { Black maintains the pin. } 9. Re1 e6
{ Time to get the other bishop out! } 10. Ne4 Be7
{ Black has all of their minor pieces out and nothing much is happening... until.... }
11. d3 f5
{ Black opens up the position since they have two bishops. Also, this eliminates the annoying white e5-pawn, if White takes en passant. }
12. exf6
{ 12.Ng3!?  Bxf3!  13.Qxf3  Qd5!  Black stands well, since they have space everywhere and the White c1-bishop doesn't have any active squares. }
12... gxf6
{ The position is dynamically equal. Black will try to play ...e6-e5, ...Qd8-d7, ...Nc7-e6, ...O-O-O, and attack the white king down the g-file. }
