6. Bxc6 dxc6
{ Black always takes with the d7-pawn so their c8-bishop has some good squares to develop. The c7-knight now has e6 and d5-squares to go to later. }
7. d3 Bf5 { Black can also play  7...Bg4  ,  but I prefer this here. } 8. Nc3
c4 { Pressuring the d3-pawn. We see this idea often in this chapter. } 9. Nh4
{ 9.dxc4!?  Qxd1  10.Rxd1  Bxc2  Black has the two bishops and no problems here. }
9... Be6 { The bishop protects the c4-pawn and gets away from the h4-knight. }
10. d4 g6
{ Black can't play ...e7-e6 anytime soon, so they play ...g6 so they can fianchetto his bishop, and, at the same time, stop White from playing f2-f4 and f4-f5 attacking the e6-bishop. }
11. f4 Qd7
{ Protecting f5 again, and leaving White wondering which way Black will castle. }
12. Ne4 Bd5 { A great square for the bishop! } 13. Nc5 Qc8
{ This position has a dynamic equality. Black will play ...e7-e6 soon and stop f4-f5 once and for all, and he can also kick out the c5-knight with ...b7-b6. }
