[Black "Rossolimo Attack - Hasty 4.e5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White's main move by far, aiming for an Open Sicilian. It's called that because after d4, Black's c-pawn and White's d-pawn are exchanged, opening some lines for active play. }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This has become quite popular over the last 20 years, and I face it almost as often as the Open Sicilian with  3.d4  . }
3... Nf6
{ This is the fourth most common move, and I want my Chessable peeps to get their opponents out of their prep ASAP, and also play something that is good for Black!   Typically, Black plays either  3...e6  @@StartBracket@@that's what I usually play@@EndBracket@@ or  3...g6  . But since your opponents will be booked to the teeth in those lines, let's make it tough for White right away! }
4. e5
{ Immediately trying to punish 3...Nf6. But this give Black the nice d5-square. }
4... Nd5 { A nice central post. } 5. O-O Nc7
{ The idea of ...Nf6-d5-c7 is seen throughout this chapter.   The b5-bishop almost always takes on c6 now, since, that was White's plan after 3. Bb5 in any case. }
6. Bxc6 dxc6
{ Black always takes with the d7-pawn so their c8-bishop has some good squares to develop. The c7-knight now has e6 and d5-squares to go to later. }
7. h3 { Stopping ...Bg4. } 7... Bf5
{ A nice developing square for the bishop. } 8. d3 c4
{ Putting pressure on the d3-pawn. This is a common idea in this chapter. The c2-pawn isn't defended if White tries to win the c4-pawn. }
9. d4
{ 9.dxc4?!  Qxd1  10.Rxd1  Bxc2  Black has the two bishops and no worries.   If Black plays ...c5-c4 in this chapter, and White takes on c4 and doesn't win a pawn, then White shouldn't take! }
9... e6 { Black has the two bishops and a grip on the White squares. } 10. Qe2
{ Attacking the c4-pawn. } 10... b5 11. b3
{ The c4-pawn is annoying so White tries to improve their queenside activity by pushing their pawns. }
11... cxb3 12. axb3 h6
{ Black doesn't play  12...Be7  since they have better plans for his dark-squared bishop! This stops White from ever playing Ng5 or Bg5, and gives Black the h7 retreat square for the f5-bishop. }
13. c4 a5
{ Black can gain space on the queenside as well! Perhaps Black can get a passed a-pawn soon. }
14. Nc3 Bb4
{ Developing with tempo. Black is at least equal with their two bishops and dynamic game. }
