[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White's main move by far, aiming for an Open Sicilian. It's called that because after d4, Black's c-pawn and White's d-pawn are exchanged, opening some lines for active play. }
2... Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This has become quite popular over the last 20 years, and I face it almost as often as the Open Sicilian with  3.d4  . }
3... Nf6
{ This is the fourth most common move, and I want my Chessable peeps to get their opponents out of their prep ASAP, and also play something that is good for Black!   Typically, Black plays either  3...e6  @@StartBracket@@that's what I usually play@@EndBracket@@ or  3...g6  . But since your opponents will be booked to the teeth in those lines, let's make it tough for White right away! }
4. Nc3 e5
{ This unusual move has been played successfully by Kramnik and Carlsen! } 5.
Bxc6 dxc6 6. Nxe5
{ White tries to win a pawn. Anand has been successful with this line for White, but, that's because he's Anand! This is only way for White to try to refute 4...e5. Otherwise Black plays ...d7-d6 and develops normally and has easy equality, if not more. }
6... Nxe4
{ Temporarily sacrificing a piece, but Black gets it back very quickly. } 7.
Nxe4 Qd4 { Forking the knights. } 8. O-O Qxe5 9. d4
{ A brilliant pawn sacrifice that gives White an initiative. This let's the c1-bishop get out more quickly. }
9... cxd4 10. Re1 Be7 { Black hastens to castle. } 11. Bg5 O-O 12. Nf6+
{ The point of White's play. } 12... Bxf6 13. Rxe5 Bxe5
{ The engine says White is slightly better, but, Black has a rook, bishop, and pawn for the queen, so material is equal, and Black should be able to play for a win here as well. }
*

