1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ This unusual move is played sometimes at the master level, but rarely with players under 2200. }
3... Nd4 4. Nf3 a6
{ Black can also play  4...Nxb5  ,  but I prefer this line for White, trying to punish the early Bb5 by kicking it around. }
5. Bd3 Nc6 { Black moves back to c6 and laughs at White's d3-bishop! } 6. O-O
d6 7. Bc4
{ White is tired of his Bishop blocking the d2-pawn!  7.b3  White can't move his d2-pawn, so, b2-b3 and fianchetto it is!  g6  Black also fianchettoes.  8.Bb2  Bg7  9.h3  This stops Black from playing ...Bc8-g4 and total control of the d4-square.  e6  Andreikin-Carlsen, 2018. The engine says Black is better, but their blitz game ended in a draw.   Black will play ...Nge7 and ...O-O with an easy game since White's d3-bishop is a bit oddly placed. }
7... Nf6 8. d4
{ Transposing to an Open Sicilian. Again, this is a line you are unlikely to face since White already decided not to play the Open Sicilian. }
8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ This trade is good, since White has to put their queen in harm's way and we can try to play ...b7-b5 soon. }
10. Qxd4 e6
{ In this variation, where white has put his Bishop on c4, it makes more sense to play e7-e6 rather than g7-g6 so we can thwart the Bishop on c4.   This is the safest way black can play, and the pawns on e6 and d6 control all the key central squares. }
11. Bg5 Be7
{ Black has completely equalized, and can play ...O-O, ...b5, ...Bb7 next, or ...Bd7-c6. }
