[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ The Closed Sicilian. The only Super-GM to play this regularly is Boris Spassky, and that was 30-60 years ago!   It is played sometimes in the U2000 level though, so it's a must-know! }
3... e6
{ This is less common than  3...g6  ,  so, your opponent will face it less and have less experience. This move should give Black at least equality, no matter what White does. The Closed Sicilian is popular at the lower levels @@StartBracket@@U2000@@EndBracket@@, but players over 2200 almost never play it since Black has more than one way to get a good position. }
4. Bg2 Nf6
{ Black develops their kingside, castles, and plays for ...d5 or ...b5 @@StartBracket@@occasionally both@@EndBracket@@. Black doesn't have any pressure on them, so White can't get an advantage. }
5. Nge2
{ If White decides to play for d2-d4, then this is the way to do it. If White never plays d2-d4, but prefers d2-d3, then that will transpose to lines where White plays d2-d3 early. This is an unusual way for White to play, since, we transpose to an Open Sicilian, which White avoided! }
5... Be7 { Develop and castle. Always a good strategy! } 6. O-O O-O 7. d4
{ Again, if White doesn't do this and plays d2-d3 and f2-f4, that transposes toother lines. }
7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 d6 9. Be3 Bd7
{ The g2-g3 lines in the Open Sicilian are not very popular for White, since, Black gets to develop and castle easily, and these positions are easy for Black to play. Black can play either ...Nxd4 and ...Bc6, or play for ...Nc4 later @@StartBracket@@with either ...Na5 or ...Ne5@@EndBracket@@ and use the half open c-file with ...Rc8.   White doesn't have an easy way to improve his position, and, in practice, Black does well from this position. }
*

