[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3
{ The Closed Sicilian. The only Super-GM to play this regularly is Boris Spassky, and that was 30-60 years ago!   It is played sometimes in the U2000 level though, so it's a must-know! }
3... e6
{ This is less common than  3...g6  ,  so, your opponent will face it less and have less experience. This move should give Black at least equality, no matter what White does. The Closed Sicilian is popular at the lower levels @@StartBracket@@U2000@@EndBracket@@, but players over 2200 almost never play it since Black has more than one way to get a good position. }
4. Bg2 Nf6
{ Black develops their kingside, castles, and plays for ...d5 or ...b5 @@StartBracket@@occasionally both@@EndBracket@@. Black doesn't have any pressure on them, so White can't get an advantage. }
5. d3 Be7 6. Nge2
{ White delays f2-f4, but, what else can they do?   But castling is always a good idea! }
6... O-O 7. O-O Rb8
{ This gets the rook off the h1-a8 diagonal, and Black may decide to play ...b7-b5 later. }
8. f4 d6 9. h3
{ White plays for kingside expansion whilst Black advances on the queenside. }
9... Bd7
{ Black defends the c6-knight, so White can't surprise him with e4-e5! Now Black is ready for ...b7-b5-b4, etc. }
10. g4 b5
{ Black has all his minor pieces out and has castled. Time to gain space! } 11.
Ng3
{ White knows Black will play ...b5-b4 next, so he frees the e2-square for his queen's knight. }
11... b4 12. Nce2 Ne8
{ Black expects White to play g4-g5, so they play ...Ne8 first, and can later play ...Ne8-c7 and play on the queenside with ...a7-a5-a4, or play ...d6-d5 in the center.   White is reluctant to play f4-f5 anytime soon since that gives Black the e5-square for their c6-knight. The engine says it is dynamically equal, but, in practice, Black scores over 65%! }
