[Round "?"]
[White "8) Gambits & Other Rare Pawn Moves"]
[Black "Smith-Morra Gambit - 2.d4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4
{ The Smith-Morra Gambit! This is quite popular at the U2200 level, but, GMs never play it, unless it's blitz or bullet.   Most GMs don't want to sacrifice a pawn on move 2! }
2... cxd4 3. c3
{ This is the real starting position of the Gambit. Of course, White could play  3.Nf3  transposing into the Open Sicilian or  3.Qxd4  ,  which isn't good since  3...Nc6  kicks the Queen.   But gambit players love playing the Smith-Morra! }
3... dxc3
{ Taking the pawn is the only way for Black to get an advantage! More tame moves that are also good are  3...Nf6  ,  3...e5  ,  and  3...d3  . }
4. Nxc3 e6
{ Black usually plays  4...Nc6  ,  but this has been played successfully by Caruana, Timman, Van Wely, and Short. }
5. Nf3 a6
{ This really makes the f1-bishop of little use in getting compensation. White likes to play Bc4 in this Gambit, but here, it is ineffective. }
6. Bc4
{ It doesn't look like the bishop does much here, but it is still, by far, the most common move. White wants to castle, and doesn't see another good square for the bishop. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 Bb7 8. O-O Be7
{ The engine move, and the one played by Caruana @@StartBracket@@I suspect Fabi knew this was the engine move!@@EndBracket@@.   Black develops their pieces and will soon just be ahead a pawn for little compensation. Black wants to block the e-file in case White sacrifices a piece with a later Nc3-d5. }
9. Qe2 Nc6 10. Rd1
{ The plan of Qe2 and Rd1 is played almost automatically by Morra players. }
10... Na5
{ Black opens up their b7-bishop and wants to take the b3-bishop and get the two bishops. }
11. Bc2 Nf6 { Black gets out their last minor piece and will soon castle. } 12.
e5 Nd5 { Black uses the d5-square for their minor pieces. } 13. Nxd5 Bxd5
{ White has compensation for the pawn, but Black is better. Black will castle and play ...Rc8 with an excellent position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Gambits & Other Rare Pawn Moves"]
[Black "Smith-Morra Gambit - 2.d4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. d4
{ The Smith-Morra Gambit! This is quite popular at the U2200 level, but, GMs never play it, unless it's blitz or bullet.   Most GMs don't want to sacrifice a pawn on move 2! }
2... cxd4 3. c3
{ This is the real starting position of the Gambit. Of course, White could play  3.Nf3  transposing into the Open Sicilian or  3.Qxd4  ,  which isn't good since  3...Nc6  kicks the Queen.   But gambit players love playing the Smith-Morra! }
3... dxc3
{ Taking the pawn is the only way for Black to get an advantage! More tame moves that are also good are  3...Nf6  ,  3...e5  ,  and  3...d3  . }
4. Nxc3 e6
{ Black usually plays  4...Nc6  ,  but this has been played successfully by Caruana, Timman, Van Wely, and Short. }
5. Nf3 a6
{ This really makes the f1-bishop of little use in getting compensation. White likes to play Bc4 in this Gambit, but here, it is ineffective. }
6. Bc4
{ It doesn't look like the bishop does much here, but it is still, by far, the most common move. White wants to castle, and doesn't see another good square for the bishop. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 Bb7 8. O-O Be7
{ The engine move, and the one played by Caruana @@StartBracket@@I suspect Fabi knew this was the engine move!@@EndBracket@@.   Black develops their pieces and will soon just be ahead a pawn for little compensation. Black wants to block the e-file in case White sacrifices a piece with a later Nc3-d5. }
9. e5 { This ends White's dreams of playing Nc3-d5 later. } 9... Nc6 10. Qe2
Na5 { Black wants the two bishops, what else? } 11. Bc2 f5
{ White has almost no compensation for a pawn.   Black has a great b7-bishop and White doesn't have anything threatening against the black king. }
12. exf6
{ White opens up the center trying to get active play for the pawn.   12.Rd1  Putting the white rook opposite the black queen.  Qc7  This pressures the pawn on e5, and gets the queen off the d-file where the white rook was pressuring.  13.Nd4  Nc6  The Knight has done its job on a5, and now gets back to the action.   Black will soon play ...Nh6 and later, ...Nf7 and castle kingside. White simply doesn't have enough compensation for the pawn minus. }
12... Nxf6
{ Black has every minor piece out and has 2 center pawns to 0. Black is clearly better here and should be very happy with his position. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Gambits & Other Rare Pawn Moves"]
[Black "Accelerated Grand Prix - 2.f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. f4
{ This is less common than the Grand Prix Attack, where, first, White plays  2.Nc3  ,  then 3. f4. This is a rare move in tournament play, and I don't remember if I've faced it in a rated game. }
2... d5
{ This has been played by Kasparov, Caruana, Giri, and Svidler! It's not a move you can easily play after 2. Nc3.   Often this involves a positional pawn sacrifice where Black gets an excellent position and White has a ragged pawn structure. }
3. exd5
{ 3.e5?!  This is usually bad when Black can easily play ...Nh6-f5. GMs never play 3. e5.  Nc6  4.Nf3  Nh6!  Heading to f5.  5.Bb5  Bd7  Black is already much better. Black has easy play with ...Nh6-f5, ...e7-e6, ...Bf7-e7, ...O-O, etc. The c1-bishop is quite bad for White. Black is already threatening ...Nxe5! winning a pawn. }
3... Nf6
{ This is better than  3...Qxd5  . This is precisely a Scandi with the moves f2-f4 for White and ...c7-c5 inserted for Black.   White playing f2-f4 makes no sense in this line. White wants the pawn duo on e4 and f4 and it's already ruined. }
4. Bb5+
{ This is, by far, the most common move.  4.c4?!  White is greedy and wants to keep his extra pawn. Black obliges!  e6!  5.dxe6  Bxe6  This is a very ugly position for White. Their pawns create holes in the e4 and especially d4 squares.   White has no development, and Black already has two pieces out. The engine already thinks Black is much better!  6.Nf3  Nc6  7.Nc3  g6!  The g7-bishop will be excellently placed on the long diagonal.  8.d3  Bg7  White's bishops are both terrible, their d3-pawn is weak and backward, and Black has excellent development and is ready to castle. The engine says 0.6: better for Black! }
4... Bd7 { 4...Nbd7  is also playable, but I like this line better. } 5. Bxd7+
Qxd7
{ If Black takes on d5 they are clearly better, so White keeps their extra pawn @@StartBracket@@but at what cost!@@EndBracket@@. }
6. c4 { Otherwise ...Nxd5 gives Black a great position. } 6... e6
{ This is typical in this line after White plays an early c2-c4. } 7. dxe6
Qxe6+ 8. Qe2
{ Trading queens doesn't help White much. Their position is still terrible with all the holes. }
8... Qxe2+ { 8...Nc6  is a good alternative played by some GMs. } 9. Nxe2 Nc6
{ The engine prefers Black. The White c1-bishop is terrible and there are too many weaknesses in the white position.   Black dominates the center squares and will likely play ...Nc6-b4 and ...O-O-O with an initiative. It's much easier to play Black here. }
*

